    content: `
      <h2>Strict Liability, Severe Consequences</h2>
      <p>The International Traffic in Arms Regulations (ITAR), administered by the Directorate of Defense Trade Controls (DDTC), is a strict liability regime. It does not matter if you "didn't mean" to export technical data to a foreign person. If you did it, you are liable. The penalties are massive - up to $1 million per violation and potential criminal prison time for individuals. More importantly for defense contractors, a violation can lead to debarment, effectively killing your ability to hold government contracts.</p>

      <h2>The "Deemed Export" Trap</h2>
      <p>You don't have to ship a missile part to violate ITAR. Showing a blueprint or discussing technical specs with a foreign national employee inside your U.S. office is a "deemed export" to that person's home country. We help companies implement Technology Control Plans (TCPs) and badging systems that firewall controlled data, allowing you to hire global talent without inadvertently breaking federal law.</p>

      <h2>Commodity Jurisdiction: Is It ITAR or EAR?</h2>
      <p>The most common question we get: "Is my product actually ITAR-controlled?" The U.S. Munitions List (USML) is broad, but not infinite. If your product has civil applications, it might fall under the less restrictive Export Administration Regulations (EAR) rather than ITAR. We file Commodity Jurisdiction (CJ) requests with the State Department to get an official determination. Moving a product from ITAR to EAR jurisdiction can open up global markets that were previously off-limits.</p>

      <h2>Agreements and Licensing</h2>
      <p>To share ITAR data with a foreign partner, you need more than a license; you often need a Technical Assistance Agreement (TAA) or Manufacturing License Agreement (MLA). These are complex legal contracts approved by the U.S. government. We draft and negotiate these agreements to ensure they cover the full scope of your program while satisfying DDTC provisos.</p>

      <h2>Voluntary Disclosures</h2>
      <p>If you find a violation, the cover-up is always worse than the crime. The Department of State incentivizes Voluntary Disclosures. If you come forward with a full account and a robust remediation plan, penalties are often mitigated to zero. We manage this delicate process, conducting the internal investigation and drafting the narrative to frame the violation as a fixable oversight rather than systemic negligence.</p>
    `
